text_sections.full_transcription:
Bouquets and Brickbats of
CLASS 9SP3

SCOTT EHRLICH—Is good in math. Fame will one day cross his path.
WARREN EISENSTEIN—'I didn't do it' is his alibi. 'It was me that talked, honest'!
STEPHEN GARONE—He will be popular in English but never win the speller.
HOWARD GLANTZMAN—Hear the noise in back of the room, kidding aside sometimes it's fun.
PAUL KAMINSKY—Paul is a genius but never shows it; we wonder if he really knows it.
CASEY KOPOWITZ—There are happy people, jealous ones and worrisome, then there are good people, there are nice people than there's Casey.
MARK LIPTON—Our captain brave and strong, How come he always looks so wrong?
JOEL MANDLEMAN—If home he says he often strains, Why, then, at loose leaves he his brains?
ELLIOT RAINES—With Eisenstein, he'll answer quickly; Ask about science, he'll answer thickly.
STEPHEN SCHWARTZ—Humpty and jolly, a great guy, by golly!
BETTY BRODSKY—Always a pleasure, always a delight, she'll lose anything she doesn't lose yet.
SHARON BROYDE—Sharon's motto will be forever 'It's always better late—than never.'
CHERYL GREENSPAN—If you need someone to brighten your way, Cheryl will do it by smiling all day.

ELLEN KATZ—Ellen is long and lanky. She studies with no hanky panky.
DEBRA NESSEL—Debbie is full of joy. Only when she's with a boy.
GALE REIF—Gale will be a secretary and you may as well clap, for she'll wind up sitting on her boss's lap.
ENID ROSEMAN—They don't come sweeter. No one can beat-er.
AUDREY ROTH—There are geese in flocks and cattle in herds. There is Audrey, who is great big words.
BARBARA SCHWARTZ—Boy and gentle, nice and sweet. The kind of girl we like to meet.
MERRIL SINGER—There are as many freckles on her face as there are hairs in Dorothy Jane.
SANDRA STEIGMAN—She will always learn is no exception.
MELODY STERN—Melody is always the center of attraction, without her around there'd never be action.
KATHLEEN SUTER—Rumpelstiltskin never spun a gold as lovely as Kathleen's hair.
JUDITH TLUMAN—Soy and quiet in her seat, doesn't Judy look just sweet!
MRS. SCHAELSTEIN—A little laugh, a little cheer, a lot of work—Mrs. Schaelstein's here!

Adieu, Adios, Auf Wiedersehen . . .
Till we meet again—
Farewell, Mark Twain.

CLASS 8-SPE

Susan Jacobs          Richard Girard
Janis Simpson         Howard Richman
Helga Sumuelisch      Jill Neihauski
Elaine E. Siseling    Elizabeth Laufer
Iris Hershenson       Joanne Morano
Allan Jeffrey Steinumer  Robbie Tislansky
Leonard Klein         Robin Miller
Lynn Henn            Robert Rosenbaum
Mr. M. Dilliker       Gary Olitit
Sybil Bess          Bernard Markowitz
Lynn Kritz           Juanita Ellen Stokes
Ian Cohen            William Eisenstein
Arnold Hoon          Janice Luby
Eric Barsky          Howard Tobak
Mark Schumer         Brigitte Bulinsky

Class 9-7

Come out of your coma
And get a diploma—
Like we did . . .

Class 9-12

and MR. PATASHNA
